SQL Server, and most RDMS&#39;s for that matter, will behave this way if the value of the column is already the value you&#39;re attempting to set.

Demo of this behaviour: http://sqlfiddle.com/#!18/8eb54/7

```tsql
CREATE TABLE [t] (
  PRIMARY KEY ([n])
  , [n] INT NOT NULL
);

INSERT INTO [t] ([n])
SELECT 1;
-- 0 Rows affected 

UPDATE [t]
SET [n] = 1
WHERE 1 = 1;
-- 0 Rows affected 

SELECT * FROM [t];
-- 1 Row returned

